<h3>
    Overview
</h3>

<p>
    Use the <code>@exports</code> tag when documenting JavaScript modules to indicate that an object is being exported.
</p>

<h3>
    Examples
</h3>

<p>
    In cases where you are using the special "exports" namespace, the <code>@exports</code> tag is never needed...
</p>

<p>
    <b>In CommonJS modules the exports namespace is understood by JSDoc 3</b>
</p>

{{#includeExample}}
    jake/extended_docs/examples/tags-exports-0.js
{{/includeExample}}

<p>
    <b>In AMD modules any namespace called "exports" is assumed by JSDoc 3 to be the exported object</b>
</p>

{{#includeExample}}
    jake/extended_docs/examples/tags-exports-1.js
{{/includeExample}}

<p>
    <b>If your AMD module exports a constructor, you can still use the "exports" name to indicate what the module is</b>
</p>

{{#includeExample}}
    jake/extended_docs/examples/tags-exports-2.js
{{/includeExample}}

<p>
    If you are exporting an object named anything other than "exports", use the <code>@exports</code> tag to indicate what is being exported.
</p>

<p>
    <b>The @exports tag is used to document that the "ns" namespace is being exported</b>
</p>

{{#includeExample}}
    jake/extended_docs/examples/tags-exports-3.js
{{/includeExample}}

{{#includeExample}}
    ../jsdoc/test/fixtures/exports.js
{{/includeExample}}
{{#includeExample}}
    ../jsdoc/test/fixtures/exportstag.js
{{/includeExample}}
{{#includeExample}}
    ../jsdoc/test/fixtures/exportstag2.js
{{/includeExample}}
{{#includeExample}}
    ../jsdoc/test/fixtures/exportstag3.js
{{/includeExample}}
{{#includeExample}}
    ../jsdoc/test/fixtures/exportstag4.js
{{/includeExample}}

